1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper deals with codes for read channels, which is a topic closely related to information theory. 
2. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The paper discusses the construction of new families of linear MDS codes, which involves the design and analysis of algorithms for encoding and decoding. 
3. cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) - The paper may have applications in distributed computing, where error-correcting codes are used to ensure reliable communication over noisy channels. 
4. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - The paper may involve some computational complexity analysis in terms of the time and space complexity of encoding and decoding algorithms. 
5. cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) - The paper may have implications for cryptography and security, as error-correcting codes are used in many cryptographic protocols to ensure confidentiality and integrity of data.
